1) What is Abstraction in Java?
Ans)  It is a technique by which we can hide the data that is not required to users. It hides all unwanted data so that users can work only with the required data.

2) When to use Abstract class in Java?
Ans) An abstract class can be used when we need to share the same method to all non-abstract sub classes with their own specific implementations.

3) What is the difference between Abstraction and Encapsulation?
Ans) Abstraction hides the implementation details from users whereas, encapsulation wraps(binds) data and code into a single unit.

4 )What is the advantage of Abstract class in Java?
Ans) (a) Abstract class makes programming better and more flexible by giving the scope of implementing abstract methods.
    (b) Programmer can implement abstract method to perform different tasks depending on the need.
    (c) We can easily manage code.

5)  What is Encapsulation in Java? 
Ans) Encapsulation is a programming technique that binds the class members (variables and methods) together and prevents them from being accessed by other classes
     thereby we can keep variables and methods safes from outside interference and misuse.

6) What does Java's inheritance mean?
Ans) Inheritance is the term used in Java to describe the process of building a new class utilizing the features of an existing class.
In other words, inheritance is how a child class acquires each parent class's traits.

7) What kinds of inheritance are there in Java?
Ans) a. Multi-level Inheritance
     b. Single Inheritance
     c. Multiple Inheritance 
     d. Hybrid Inheritance and,
     e. Hierarchical Inheritance
